uthor of Environmental History in China and the West: Its Origins and Prospects This book is a multidisciplinary study of the ecology of China’s early political systems up to the fall of the first empire in 207 BCE. Brian Lander traces the formation of lowland North China’s agricultural systems and the transformation of its plains from diverse forestland and steppes to farmland. He argues that the growth of states in ancient China, and elsewhere, was based on their ability to exploit the labor and resources of those who harnessed photosynthetic energy from domesticated plants and animals. Focusing on the state of Qin, Lander amalgamates abundant new scientific, archaeological, and excavated documentary sources to argue that the human domination of the central Yellow River region, and the rest of the planet, was made possible by the development of complex political structures that managed and expanded agroecosystems.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAgriculture and state-China-History. 0aChina-History. 0aChina-Politics and government-To 221 B.C. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/9780300262728?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300262728423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300262728/original  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles